{title: Atlanta Anymore}
{artist: Gene Watson}
{composer: Written by Charlie Craig and Keith Stegall}

[G]Inside a suit coat pocket in the back of his closet today
She found a letter among the bills he forgot to pay
It was [C]addressed to a woman a name she'd never seen before
It started [G]out I'm sorry but I [D7]won't be in Atlanta any[G]more
As she read the words he'd written she found it hard to believe her eyes
At first she was angry then slowly she began to cry
Cause [C]somewhere down in Georgia he'd taken off the wedding ring he wore
And it didn't [G]help a whole lot knowing that he [D7]won't be in Atlanta any[G]more
He said I [C]won't be in Atlanta any[G]more
And I'm [Em]sorry that I lied to you [G]before
The truth [C]is I got a wife and two [G]children three and [C]four
And I [G]won't be in [D7]Atlanta any[G]more
At the bottom of the last page he'll never know the PS that she wrote
Cause she folded up the pages and slipped them back into the envelope
Then she [C]took the goodbye letter and dropped it in the mailbox on the porch
She thought the [G]woman ought to know that [D7]Atlanta's not a secret any[G]more
She wrote he [C]won't be in Atlanta any[G]more
And I [Em]don't know why he lied to you [G]before
But God [C]knows I still love him and [G]I'm just makin' [C]sure
That he [G]won't be in [D7]Atlanta any[G]more
He wrote it and she mailed it
He [D7]won't be in Atlanta any[G]more